result.execSummary:
The defendant Jacob W Musil was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/Intent-THC (<=200 grams), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(h)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Defendant Jacob W Musil in court with attorney James Edwin Gatzke.  Andrea M. Will appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant enters a guilty plea to Count 1.  Court finds defendant guilty. Ct. 2 and Ct. 3 dismissed and read-in. 

Court orders the following: 
Ct. 1:
-  Withheld sentence for 3 years Probation
- Court Costs of: $268.00 to be paid as a Condition of Probation 
- Restitution of $245.23 to be paid to Paul B.  as a Condition of Probation.
- DNA Surcharge of $250.00 to be paid as a Condition of Probation
- Conditions of  Probation: Maintain absolute sobriety. Random U.A.'s..  AODA assessment and follow through with any treatment/counseling.  No use or possession of alcohol or controlled substances without a valid prescription. No drug paraphernalia. Any valid prescription drugs must be taken only in the manner in which they are prescribed; Inform Agent of all prescriptions. Maintain full-time employment and/or combination of schooling or any other approved activity by agent. No contact with Hannah B. or Peter M. or their residences. Anger Management as deemed appropriate by the Agent and any other counseling recommended.   Defendant to provide DNA sample, if not yet provided,  immediately if in custody otherwise within (3) business days at the Waukesha County Sheriff Department. 
 - 10 days jail Condition Time (nonworking hours) STAYED to be used at the Agents discretion. Huber/Straight time to be used at Agent's discretion.

Expungement addressed.
State has no objection to expungement.
If Defendant completes Probation successfully without any violations and has no new law violations, Court finds it in the defendant's interest to grant expungement and society would not be harmed.
